guardrails_result.guardrails_completion_text:
To render green text on a terminal emulator that supports ANSI escape codes, such as most Unix/Linux terminals or some graphical interfaces like tmux, you use the following escape sequence: `\033[32m`. Here's what happens technically:


When you type `\033[32m` into your terminal, the terminal recognizes the first two characters (`\033`) as an escape charactera signal that the subsequent characters should form an escape sequence rather than being interpreted literally. In this case, `\033` is immediately followed by `[`, indicating the start of the control sequence.


The number `32` that follows the opening square bracket specifies the attribute to set; in this case, it corresponds to the "foreground" color attribute, and the decimal value `32` indicates the color green.


After issuing the green color code, you can type whatever text you want to appear in green. Once you are done typing your colored text, you must reset the terminal attributes to their default state by sending the escape sequence `\033[0m`. This sequence tells the terminal that the previous settings (in this case, the green color) should no longer apply, and normal terminal behavior resumes.


Here's how the entire process looks in practice:

```plaintext
$ echo -ne '\033[32mThis text will be green!\033[0m'
This text will be green!
```

In this example, the outputted string appears in green because of the preceding ANSI escape code.


It's worth mentioning that while VT100 did indeed define a range of escape sequences for controlling various aspects of the terminal interface, specific color codes weren't initially included in the specification. Over time, however, they became widely adopted practices for terminal applications.
